  (text "1. 12V Barrel Jack Input.\n2. 12V to 3.3V Buck converter. This utilizes the MP2338GTL-P buck converting IC. The circuitry to get the input from 12V to 3.3V\nwas derived from the MP2338GTL-P's datasheet as it has a tutorial for choosing RLC values, as well as just shows a 12V to 3.3V buck \nconverting circuit that uses the MP2338GTL-P.\n3. 16 Pin USB-C receptacle. This will the ESP32 to the computer on the PCB in order for us to program the ESP32 while demoing and \ndebugging the PCB. In this configuration, we are establishing the PCB as the downstream device and only taking the data pins from \nthe USB-C.\n4. CH340C. This is the USB-C to UART ESP32 programmer that will be used. The circuit uses the transistors to switch on and off EN/IO1\nto program the ESP32. It takes in input from the USB-C data pins directly and converts those data signals into a UART message to \nprogram the ESP32 with.\n5. ESP32-WROOM-E. The microcontroller used to interface with all of the peripherals and send data back and forth between the vapes \nESP32.\n6. UV LED driving circuit. This circuit will be done on another PCB than the main Home Base board, hence the connector pins that will\nbe used to interconnect the ESP32 on the main Homebase board to the UV LED PCB. This PCB will include the 295nm UV LED and the LED\ndriver that will act as a constant current source for the UV LED. This LED will take the 12V input from the main board and use a \nreference resistance governed by Iout = 0.1 / Rf to set Iout for the UV LED. To get a 20mA current for the UV LED, the Rf then should \nbe 5 ohms. The inductor is used to smooth out Iout in order for the most consistent 20mA Iout needed to drive the UV LED at a constant\nrate, which will be most important for out photodiode light detection.\n7. Photodiode and Transimpedence Amplifier circuit. The current generated by the photodiode will be turned into an output voltage \nacross the OPA380AID amplifier by the feedback loop. The output current generated by the photodiode is hard to give an exact value for \nat this point in design, so after some calculations the expected possible output current and resulting output voltages with given \nresistors will be shown by Note 1. To get the exact amount of current and output voltage, we will have to do some testing with the \nphotodiode once we get it, leading Rf to be variable for now as we don't know how much we want to amplify it to.\n8 - 10. Load Cell and Amplifier circuit. The amplifier will be a premade module by SparkFun, hence the connector pins tying the external \namplifier board to the Homebases main board. The resistor dividers in these circuits are the load cells. The load cell cuircuit model\n(the resistor dividers) was depicted by SparkFun on their assembly guide of the load cell amplifiers.\n11 - 13. Pump driver circuit. These are the Adafruit DRV8871 single motor - motor driving circuits. These are going to be external to the \nmain Homebase board so we have connector pins to communicate between PCB boards." 
    (exclude_from_sim no) 
    (at 15.748 252.984 0) 
    (effects 
      (font 
        (size 1.27 1.27)) 
      (justify left)) 
    (uuid "c4aead07-5bf6-489b-ab32-214b571c26d5")) 
